10: NA)","Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Enrique, Jaime, Manuel, Miguel, Ofelia, Ricardo, Salvador, Andres, Argentina, Armando.","Hispanic (<b>Guitiérrez</b>): altered form of Spanish <b>Gutiérrez</b> (see   Gutierrez  )."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Toledo","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Luis, Jorge, Manuel, Ramon, Rafael, Juan, Antonio, Jesus, Miguel, Roberto, Carlos, Francisco.","Spanish and Jewish (Sephardic): habitational name from the city in central Spain, which was the capital of the Visigothic state between the 6th and 8th centuries. Its role declined for three centuries after the Muslim invasion of Spain, until it was taken as the capital of the kingdom of Castile between the 11th and 16th centuries. It was a major cultural and political center throughout the Middle Ages, and was also the home of an important Jewish community. The placename, first recorded in Latin as <i>Toletum</i>, is of obscure etymology, possibly connected with <i>Toleto</i> in Piedmont; Jewish tradition connects it with Hebrew <i>toledot</i> ‘generations’, but this is no more than folk etymology. Compare   Toledano  .","Jewish (Sephardic): also an adoption of the Spanish surname (see 1 above) at the moment of conversion to Roman Catholicism. After the return to Judaism (generations later), some descendants retained the surname their families used as Catholics."],"variants":[{"name":"Toledano","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Shlomo, Igal, Moshe, Shimon, Ehud, Shmuel, Yehuda.  Spanish Alberto, Gonzalo, Alina, Carlos, Conrado, Elena, Enrique, Evelia, Luis, Manuel, Miguel, Ramona.  French Gabrielle, Michel.","Spanish and Jewish (Sephardic): habitational name for someone from Toledo (see   Toledo  ), from an adjectival form of the placename."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Doña Horabuena Gutiérrez de Toledo was born about 1259, in New Castile, Spain, her father, Gutiérrez Armíldez de Toledo, Prior de la O. de San Juan, was 29 and her mother, Mayor Fernández, was 23. She had at least 2 sons and 2 daughters with Gomez Perez De Toledo Y Palomeque. She died on 4 October 1334, in Spain, at the age of 76."},"et":{"about 1259–4 October 1334":"umbes 1259–4. oktoober 1334","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","1259–1334":"1259–1334","1256–Male":"1256–Surnud","1275–1334":"1275–1334","1282–1331":"1282–1331","1284–1319":"1284–1319","1288–Female":"1288–Surnud","1231–Male":"1231–Surnud","1237–Female":"1237–Surnud","aproximadamente1288":"1288","4 October 1334":"4. oktoober 1334","1275":"1275","1231":"1231","1284":"1284","1282":"1282","1237":"1237","1259":"1259","23 October 1331":"23. oktoober 1331","1258":"1258","1334":"1334","1256":"1256","about 1259":"umbes 1259","1288":"1288","1331":"1331","1210":"1210","1319":"1319","about 1284":"umbes 1284","Murcia, Murcia, Murcia, Spain":"Murcia, Región de Murcia, Hispaania","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Hispaania","New Castile, Spain":"New Castile, Hispaania","España":"Hispaania","Spain":"Hispaania"},"fi":{"about 1259–4 October 1334":"noin 1259–4. lokakuuta 1334","1210–Male":"1210–Kuollut","1259–1334":"1259–1334","1256–Male":"1256–Kuollut","1275–1334":"1275–1334","1282–1331":"1282–1